First, you'll need to write some code that will go through every checkbox on the page, check them all, and then trigger the save functionality. Here’s a little snippet to get you started:

```javascript
document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', function() {
    // Select all checkboxes on the page
    const checkboxes = document.querySelectorAll('input[type="checkbox"]');

    // Check each checkbox
    checkboxes.forEach(function(checkbox) {
        checkbox.checked = true;
    });

    // Now, let's create a magical "Save" button
    const saveButton = document.createElement('button');
    saveButton.textContent = 'Save';
    saveButton.style.marginTop = '10px'; // Just for fun

    // Add an event listener to the button
    saveButton.addEventListener('click', function() {
        // Since we've already checked all the boxes, this is just for show.
        console.log("All checkboxes are already checked!");
    });

    // Append the button to the body (or any other container)
    document.body.appendChild(saveButton);
});
```

Remember, this is just a basic example. In a real-world scenario, you might want to add some error handling, maybe make sure the "Save" button only appears after the checkboxes have been interacted with, or even implement some kind of confirmation dialog to ensure the user really wants to save everything.

